Tony asks us to examine the aftermath for the returning soldier.  In my case, I was in a confused haze.  I got back in July, '69, and had a few more months in my enlistment to complete.  Went to Marine Corps Air Station at Santa Ana, California.  I was still a snuffy (low-ranking enlisted).  
<p>
Veteran's Day rolled around and they needed bodies to march in lines for the public.  I "volunteered."  Then they told us that protesters might well block our path.  We were not to strike out at them or break ranks, we were told, but if they laid down in our path we were to feel free to step on them.  
<p>
Naturally, I approached this event with some trepidation.  We marched in the parade and I pretty much kept eyes front.  I remember only two comments I heard from the crowd.  From an older man, "Here come the Marines!!"  From a young lady, "Smile!".  There were no protests; just lots of folks standing around waving little flags.
<p>
Got out in December '69.  Started school at the University of New Mexico in January of 1970.  The Kent State and Jackson State incidents happened May of 1970.  The day after the student deaths at Kent State, I showed up for freshman English, wearing my "1st Marine Division - Vietnam" sweatshirt. (I liked the shirt--still have it--it was given to me in 'Nam by a man I really admired.)  There were pickets in front of every entrance, urging us to strike.  Me and another vet stood there looking at each other, wondering what the hell to do.  We decided the GI Bill was paying for this, so we were gonna go to class.  We crossed the picket lines.  Nobody said word one to us.  We got to class, went in and, thank God, there were other folks there waiting for classs to begin.  We sat down to wait.  Nobody else came in--not even the instructor.  I looked around the room.  EVERY SINGLE PERSON in that room--must have been 10-12 people--was a 'Nam vet.  That's when it hit me that we were different.
<p>
