Somewhere in these discussions, someone noted the absence of a right-wing conservative in our dialogue.  Well, I am that right wing conservative--at least I was at the time of the war.  
<p>
I abhored those who protested the war because I felt they were protesting the men
who were risking their lives to save America.  I know differently now but,
at the time my husband was fighting, I was angered by those of you who
marched and carried placards against the war.  In my mind you were throwing
dirt in the faces of the soldiers who were defending your country, and many nights
I wept over that.  
<p>
I let my husband go to Vietnam because I thought he was defending his country and another country against communism.  As far as I was concerned, the draft-dodgers were cowards or just a product of the '60s mentality--anti-establishment hippies who had nothing better to do with their time than smoke pot and protest.
<p>
I am from a small-town rural area in the Midwest, and we believed our president when he said we needed to fight the war.  But, my husband says, after he arrived in-country, it wasn't long before he realized that it was an exercise in futility to be there.  Take over a firebase....lose it to the enemy...take it over again...lose it to the enemy.  Watch his buddies die....no time for grieving...move on.
<p>
It was that vicious cycle of events and the anti-war protesters from home, the cries of "baby killer" at the airports, and coming home to friends and family who never even asked him about what had happened over there that began the downward spiral that became post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) and a hardened attitude toward life.  He had had a traumatic experience the night he was wounded and he felt he had to hide that from everyone, including me.  He lived with that secret until three months ago when he trusted me enough with the information.  I felt honored.
<p>
He often woke up in the middle of the night with flashbacks, and I didn't even really ask him about them.  We moved on with our lives--at least I did--as if he hadn't ever been gone.  After all, he had come home and we could settle down.  In the first two years of our marriage, we had moved nine times to five different states.  Now that he was back home, it was time to get our feet into something permanent.
<p>
My husband went from being a platoon leader responsible for protecting his men to being a father and husband responsible for protecting his wife and children.  His demeanor never changed.  He was strong, and no one could get through to the real man.  He said he had a mental switch mechanism in Vietnam that he used to shut off the fear and horror he experienced.  When he came home, he used the same switch on me and our children.  The caring, sensitive man I had married had disappeared.  I had only known him for a year before he went to Vietnam. 
<p>
These are just a few of the things that impacted our family.  My husband has been a hard worker, successful at his job.  He has two children that he is just beginning to get to know now that they are grown and gone from home.  After 28-plus years together, my husband and I have separated.  Hopefully, we can work through the layers of time to find out who our real selves have become.
<p>
The prejudice and hatred that he feels for politicians and the Vietnamese have been prevelant for 27 years.  I am sad about that because I'm a very open-minded person--at least I have become one over the years.
<p>
Thanks for the opportunity to tell my (our) story.
<p>
