To Laura:
<p>
I know what you meant when you wrote in your bio about how your kids had to walk on eggshells around their Viet vet dad.   Like yours, I was one of those children.
<p>
I guess what I am trying to say is that I empathize with you, Laura.  I understand a lot of the "quiet warrior" stance you're talking about in your husband.  I see that in my dad to this day.  And, sadly, it rubbed off on me.  I still don't understand...  I finally decided to get that book everyone was talking about--ACHILLES IN VIETNAM.  I figure it might help me figure out my dad... might help me figure out me.  
<p>
Sometimes I wonder if there are links between my own combat experience in the Gulf, and my dad's in Vietnam.  I came back from the war in the Gulf, I drank to kill the pain, stop the dreams and numb myself to human contact which seemed almost horrifying at the time.  About six months after I came back from the Gulf  I got divorced. Five days later I got in a wreck and was comatose for four days.  Spent three months in the Navy hospital.. Fourteen surgeries later (got a bone infection), I'm finally out of the hospital for good, I think.  But so much of this trouble, I think, came from the fact that I didn't know how to talk about what I did, what I saw in the war.  Anyway, the crux of my story is that the wreck helped me find out I not only had a severe drinking problem when I came back, but that I suffered from Post Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD). 
<p>
I know this discussion is about Vietnam, but I feel what I am talking about is directly related, both through my exposure to my dad's unhealthy behavior, and my own carrying of the burden that I do.  I apologize to the group in advance if I tend to ramble a bit about my own experiences and problems post-war.
<p>
We're never going to learn unless we decide to play an active role in our society and government.  I applaud people like Tony and the others here who played an active role in protesting the war.  Not only did you protest, but you made people think for a moment.  Which is probably why a lot of them didn't like you so very much.  We tend to avoid the
unpleasant truth and stick to the well-worn path.
<p>
