I have been doing a lot of thinking about the dialogues we've had, and about the biographies.  I think, although I'm not completely sure, that I'm perhaps the oldest in the group (I'm 51 right now), and also perhaps the least stressed of the group by my experiences in Vietnam.  In Asian cultures, being the oldest imparts the ability to stand up and say what I feel as a respected elder.  In this tradition, I'd like to explore for a moment
why people were stressed by Vietnam more than other major world events.
<p>
In looking at my experience, I see a couple of things you should know.  When I turned 18, my intention was to go on to college.  But I also needed to register for the draft.  I did so, and when the form came to that passage which stated something like "Do you object to killing of another human being in a conscientious manner?" I marked the "Yes" box.  I thought it was fairly obvious that someone would object to such a statement.
<p>
My parents talked to me a week or so later when we got the conscientious objector form in the mail.  Dad had served in World War II,  and we discussed what this meant to me, and what my faith taught. (I was an Episcopalian at the time; I'm now a Lutheran.)  This was one of the few times we really discussed this aspect of life, and I ultimately withdrew the objection.
<p>
During my basic training, I learned of the need for pararescuemen, and volunteered.  I served my first year in training, then went on to Okinawa, Korea, Bermuda, and finally in Florida.  I was coming close to the time when I could leave the service, but I hadn't served in Vietnam. So, I volunteered to extend my enlistment to serve there.  I actually volunteered and withdrew the volunteer slip twice before making the final commitment.
<p>
I went to Vietnam as a volunteer with a mission of saving people's lives, not taking lives.  The mission was consistent with my own faith, and my own personal mission.  Yes, people were hurt, even killed, in doing this mission, but it was a mission I believed in, and still do.  Our squadron was responsible for over 600 lives saved during that war, and received the Presidential Unit Citation for our efforts.
<p>
Why am I going through all this?  The answer is simple.  I never compromised my own personal beliefs while participating in Vietnam.  I feel that much of the personal stress, the PTSD, that veterans feel was due to their having compromised their own beliefs in order to do what the country asked them to do.  Whether the cause was "just" or not is, to some veterans, and important part of justifying the actions they had to take while over there.  So when we disagree about the "justness" of the cause, remember that this is very important to the well-being now of some veterans.
<p>
I also feel that the stress that war protesters felt, and still feel, has to do with a government which they perceive(d) tried to make them compromise their own personal values.  This, as much as anything, may have led to what we see as fairly entrenched positions about the war seen during these discussions.
<p>
One other aspect which I feel influences what kind of stress we feel from events is a measure of what control we perceive we had over the situations we faced. We Americans have a great need to control our circumstances.  When we are not in control, such as happens with a great, earth-shattering event (for which I think Vietnam qualifies), we experience a great deal of stress.
<p>
