I find it interesting that John's state of mind is very similar to one of my cousins. (I mentioned in my bio I have a cousin, who served in Vietnam as a Marine, and came back badly wounded.) This cousin is, to this day, fairly untroubled by the war. Although his views about the "goodness" of the war have altered over time, I think he is proud that he served his country and that he had courage under fire. I suspect that he did nothing that eats at his conscience.  He came back to a military family that valued his sacrifice, even if he felt the rest of the world more or less ignored it. 
<p>
Nevertheless, he was certainly affected by the war.  In fact, he developed a long-term interest in Asia, learned Mandarin and has spent many years as a rangeland advisor to herdsmen in Mongolia. This work came, at least in part, out of his desire to go back and "do something constructive" in Asia.
<p>
On a kind of opposite note, I recently asked a friend if he believed that
the opposition to the war really cooled with the end of the draft.  In other words, as many hawks have said, was the idealism of the anti-war movement really a cover for fear and
self-preservation?  I have always thought this was another myth created to discredit us.
<p>
My friend at first was perplexed that I wanted to talk about the war at all.
His feeling was: "It's in the past and the less said about it, the better."   He was opposed to the war, though not an activist.  After graduation from college, he suddenly entered the Peace Corps. He was in one of the last groups to get a deferment for doing so.  His public position was clear: he was willing to serve his country, but would rather do it by helping than by killing.  He still believes this.  But now, as an older man, he also told me that, without a doubt, his fear for his own survival was the prime motivating factor for his decision. So he lives with at least some degree of gnawing doubt about cowardice and lack of manhood, even though he still believes he made the right choice.  The self-doubt he associates with Vietnam is part of what has made him reluctant to think or talk about the war.  
<p>
Finally, I have mentioned that I've become aware, over time, of my own privilege at having a college deferment.  Many, if not most, kids from my town and my economic background went into the service... and went to 'Nam.  I was lucky.  I got a scholarship and my deferment lasted 'til the end of college, after which my number never came up. 
<p>
Still, even during those years, I was somewhat tormented by that fact.  I felt that I was in some sense betraying my roots--taking a middle-class route out of what was being fought as a working-class war.  In 1973, I started talking about dropping out of college and enlisting.  My sister dissuaded me, and I think it was a lot of talk, anyway.  But it revealed my conflict: was it somehow cowardly to escape the war?  Intellectually, I was totally opposed to the war but, emotionally, I wondered if the military would have "made a man out of me" as, much earlier, it had my two brothers.  
<p>
These things are very complex; I think we all have a variety of skeletons rattling in our psychic closets. 
<p>
